        "text": "29 minutes ago, zaphod said:\n\nOK, good. Let's say that I had a Raspberry Pi - which I believe can use HDMI-CEC from your TV's remote. So this would give you a pretty icon and then you could still use the transport controls, etc from the TV's IR commands?\n\ntypically its the other way the PI would be controlling the tv not the tv controlling the PI.\n\nif you are using the PI for media playback you should check out plex and Kodi drivers @alanchow they work phonemically well and would give you transport controls with the apps. However I do not for sure that they control Pi\n\n@msgreenf on -topic great drivers thank you\n\nI don't really use C4 for controlling my AV devices as I am happy using my Harmony remotes at the 8-9 TVs in my house. I don't want to buy that many C4 Controllers and/or remotes the family is used to using the Harmony Remotes.\n\nI play around with Plex a bit on iOS, Xbox and RPi, but mainly for video playback I use SageTV as I have SageTV extenders at all of my TVs and I have SageTV with multiple TV tuners (some connected to cable STBs) running on an unRAID server. IMHO SageTV continues to be the best DVR option available if you are tech-savvy, although Plex, Kodi, etc may be better for the playback of recorded video files. But neither of them are that good when it comes to DVRing TV content and the other programs that I have used to do that through the years, like BeyondTV and Windows MCE, have gone by the wayside. SageTV was dying but has somewhat come back to life as Google open-sourced it a couple of years ago and there is a bit of a development community. But the need for DVRs will go away in the near future as we move away from linear programming."
